[1] Thailand
Date: Fri, 18 Nov 2005
From: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>
Source: TNA via MCOT.NET, 17 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://etna.mcot.net/query.php?nid=4533>

The central province of Lopburi is being designated a bird flu exemplar and
research area following the province's swift curbing of its avian influenza
outbreak, according to the interior minister, who praised the cooperation
shown among varied public agencies and local volunteer health workers.
During his visit to the province to observe the local authorities'
preventive and surveillance measures to contain the spead of avian flu, air
chief marshal Kongsak Wanthana said Lopburi examplifies the effective
control of the spread of the H5N1 strain of avian influenza virus.
While Lopburi is well-known as an army garrison and training centre, it is
also an industrial centre and commercial poultry production centre. During
his visit here ACM Kongsak inspected a local chicken farm.
Lopburi, located 150 km north of Bangkok, was hit by the bird flu outbreak
but it effectively curbed the outbreak in a relatively short time and was
able to systematically control the movement of poultry.
"There's good cooperation here from all directions," ACM Kongsak said, as
he praised the performance of provincial health volunteers. "People want to
maintain the standard of Lopburi's chicken farms to be a centre of chicken
exports," he said.
The minister said he would inspect problem areas and would hold a seminar
for information exchange. Provincial governors, he said, would be invited
to join the seminar to [learn about] more comprehensive measures to fight
the deadly disease along with study of Lopburi's work as a guideline.
The interior minister said cockfighting rings have not yet reopened in
Lopburi. Cockfighting isn't banned there, but local residents voluntarily
shut down their matches to help prevent the spread of bird flu.
As the main centre of the Royal Thai Army outside of Bangkok, the province
enjoys a high standard of education, awareness and public spirit in working
together for community well-being.
--
Joseph P Dudley, PhD
Research Associate
Institute of Arctic Biology - University of Alaska Fairbanks
Department of Earth Science - University of Alaska Museum
<fnjpd@uaf.edu>
[Joe Dudley added the following just remark: "It is interesting to note
that the voluntary cessation of cockfighting by local communities is
highlighted in this government press release as a key and praiseworthy
factor in the successful control of H5N1 outbreaks in poultry in Lopburi
Province". - Mod.AS]
