[4] China, Hong Kong SAR, preventive measures
Date: Fri, 18 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong Government press release, 18 Nov 2005
<http://www.news.gov.hk/en/category/healthandcommunity/051118/html/051118en05004.htm>

Hong Kong has adopted a multi-disciplinary, cross-sectoral approach to
prevent infectious diseases and an influenza pandemic, Permanent Secretary
for Health, Welfare & Food Carrie Yau says.
In a meeting with the Dutch Ministry's of Agriculture's Renee Bergkamp, Mrs
Yau said international collaboration is important in the control of avian
flu so expertise and resources can be pooled to curb the disease's spread.
Noting that the Netherlands is a close partner of Hong Kong, Mrs Yau said
the meeting was a constructive one with valuable information exchanged,
particularly on avian flu prevention. She said Hong Kong has learned a lot
from the Netherlands' experience in central slaughtering facilities and
from their computer system on infectious disease.
"[We] share the view that governments should prepare policy briefs on
infectious diseases to communicate with the public and enhance their
awareness, ability and action in the prevention and protection against
infectious diseases," Mrs Yau said.
"Both of us agree that the control of avian influenza requires co-operation
between different government institutions responsible for agriculture and
for public health, national and international research institutions, and
multilateral organisations. In Hong Kong, we treasure our experience from
the SARS outbreak and we have adopted the multi-discipline, cross-sectoral
approach to prevent infectious diseases and influenza pandemic."
Mrs Bergkamp shared Mrs Yau's view that a concerted effort will be needed
from the community in view of the recent global bird flu outbreak. "Only a
well-organised and concerted action for eradication and prevention across
the region can reduce risks and restore trade relations. Humans can become
infected by close contact with infected birds, and open markets are our
major concern," she said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Hong Kong has proven remarkably able to energetically tackle avian
influenza HPAI H5N1 since its initial detection there in 1997.
Collaboration with the Netherlands -- a country which had to kill about 30
million birds during the H7N7 outbreak in 2003 while applying newly
drafted, original biosecurity measures to protect humans from infection --
is based upon mutual interests and will be beneficial for the region,
including China. - Mod.AS]
